	<h2>Cheh is for China</h2>
	
	<p>Let&rsquo;s say we&rsquo;re reading Ferdowsi&rsquo;s culture-shaping Persian epic, the <em>Sh&acirc;hn&acirc;meh</em>, and we run into names like Manouchehr or Bahram Chubin, heroes who are <em>ch&acirc;l&acirc;k</em> (&ldquo;agile&rdquo;), perhaps <em>ch&acirc;reh-gar</em> (&ldquo;resourceful&rdquo;) or <em>chireh</em> (&ldquo;victorious&rdquo;). Or who rise to meet a challenge (<em>ch&acirc;lesh</em>). We have at hand a vocabulary of epic heroism, with a letter you will not find in the Arab world, where the sound CH does not exist. An alphabet without CH would be incomplete in Persian, Turkish and Urdu as well. (I&rsquo;m oversimplifying. In Urdu, where the same letter is called Chim, on analogy with Arabic Jim, it represents two separate CH sounds. Long story). The sound exists, I am told, in Iraqi dialect (but not represented by Cheh).&nbsp;</p>
	<p>At one time, evidently, it was a problematic sound in English orthography too. After all, we need two letters to render it, which tells us something. The French need three (<em>tch</em>), or sometimes four (<em>tsch</em>). The two letters of English CH create some awkward moments too. How do you double it? How do we transcribe in English the Persian word for &ldquo;child,&rdquo; which sounds something like &ldquo;batch-che&rdquo;? In Persian we would write the word with three letters: Ba, Cheh and an &ldquo;eh&rdquo; sound (shown by the letter H &mdash; there are reasons). The Arabic and Persian alphabets don&rsquo;t show double letters by writing them twice (there&rsquo;s a diacritical mark available for it if you like, something like a little rounded W), so the word in Persian is three letters; <strong>&#1576;&#1670;&#1607;</strong> But if you&rsquo;re going to be precise in English, what can you write but the barely readable <em>bachcheh</em>, with a double CH? We use up a lot of letters (eight versus the Persian three). And even in transcription it&rsquo;s not immediately obvious how to pronounce <em>bachcheh</em>. In Italian, where a single-letter CH-sound exists, it would be easier: <em>bacc&egrave;</em> (with the double C of <em>accento </em>or <em>accidente</em>).&nbsp;</p>
	<p>There are the epic Cheh words familiar to readers of Ferdowsi, but domestic and homely ones are probably more common. A <em>chup&acirc;n </em>is a shepherd. (It&rsquo;s the origin of Choban, the brand of yoghurt, from Turkish <em>&ccedil;oban</em>.) A <em>chupuq</em> is a pipe. A <em>chakosh</em> is a hammer. A <em>ch&acirc;qu</em> is a small knife. <em>Charb</em> is grease. <em>Chap</em> is &ldquo;left,&rdquo; as in &ldquo;left hand&rdquo; or &ldquo;leftist.&rdquo; A <em>chatr</em> is an umbrella. A <em>ch&acirc;h</em> is a well. <em>Ch&acirc;h-dalv</em> is Aquarius. (A <em>dalv</em>, Arabic <em>dalw</em>, is a bucket.) <em>Cheshm</em> means &ldquo;eye,&rdquo; and with a suffix -<em>eh</em>, it becomes <em>cheshmeh</em>, a spring or source. (For some reason the Arabic word for eye, <em>&lsquo;ayn</em>, also doubles as the word for a spring or source &mdash; without a suffix.) A <em>chah&acirc;r-p&acirc;</em> is a quadruped, since <em>chah&acirc;r</em> is Persian for the number four, and <em>p&acirc;</em> is a foot. (The more scientific equivalent is <em>charandeh</em>, grazing animals, from the verb <em>charidan</em>, to graze.) Grazing takes place in a <em>chamanz&acirc;r</em>, a meadow.&nbsp;</p>
	<p>There is a town by the name of Chaman in the north of Afghanistan, on the border with Pakistan. (The border is porous, and this has become a source of trouble in the Afghanistan conflict.) At the time of this writing, it would not have much appeal for a tourist. But years ago, in very different times, an Italian friend fluent in Persian observed that he would have liked to have one of those signs on his car that suggests an itinerary. (Like Akron/Haight-Ashbury, Paris/Tibet, or in the 1850s &ldquo;Pike&rsquo;s Peak or bust.&rdquo;) The sign he suggested would read Prato (in Tuscany) on the left and Chaman on the right. Prato means <em>chaman</em>. Both names mean a meadow or a field. So the epic car trip would take on a circular quality.&nbsp;</p>
	<p>A<em> ch&acirc;dor </em>is a tent. I&rsquo;m told that in Bengali <em>chader</em> means &ldquo;cloth.&rdquo; In Iran a <em>chador</em> is also a particular kind of veil &mdash; a semicircle of cloth, worn wrapped around the body, including the head, like a very long coat with a hood, with the face open. One holds it with the hand at the neck, to be tightened or loosened depending who is nearby. Black is the color for the more conservative. There is a style in white cotton (for prayer, a <em>chador-nam&acirc;z</em>, <em>nam&acirc;z being </em>&ldquo;prayer&rdquo;). The style I&rsquo;ve seen most in Iran is made of Cheh word <em>chit </em>(pronounced &ldquo;cheat&rdquo;), chintz with a floral pattern. (A variant, <em>ch&acirc;deri</em>, is the word used to describe a <em>burqu&lsquo;</em>, English burka, that much more restrictive veil worn in Afghanistan, something like a portable prison with a cover over the face which looks like a fencer&rsquo;s mask.)&nbsp;</p>
	<p>A <em>chughundar</em> is a beet, homely vegetable made more homely still because, I am told, it used to be an insulting term to describe a woman wrapped in a <em>ch&acirc;dor</em>.&nbsp;</p>
	<p>In contemporary Turkish orthography, the J sound of the letter Jim is represented by the letter C. To make it an unvoiced sound, English CH, one simply adds a little stroke underneath called a <em>&ccedil;engel</em>, something like a French cedilla: &ccedil;. Thus <em>&ccedil;ehre </em>is for face, <em>&ccedil;esme</em> for spring, <em>&ccedil;oban </em>for shepherd, <em>&ccedil;ubuq</em> for &ldquo;pipe,&rdquo; <em>&ccedil;&uuml;g&uuml;ndur </em>(or<em> &ccedil;ukundur</em>) for <em>chughundar.</em> The name changes. The thing remains.&nbsp;</p>
	

