	<h3>Thing</h3>
	<p><em>Chiz</em>, the word for &ldquo;thing&rdquo; in Persian, a homonym of English &ldquo;cheese,&rdquo; a cognate of French <em>chose</em>, is not strictly speaking a question word, but it is by nature vague and undefined. It doesn&rsquo;t specify what the thing is. And so you may hear &ldquo;<em>cheh chizi</em> &hellip;&rdquo; &ldquo;what thing &hellip;&rdquo; as in &ldquo;<em>cheh chizi bar&acirc;ye p&acirc;k kardan-e lakkeh-ye morakkab-e Chin khub ast</em>,&rdquo; &ldquo;what [what thing] should I use to erase an ink stain?&rdquo; As one says in Italian <em>che cosa</em> (&ldquo;what thing?&rdquo;) or in modern Greek <em>ti pragma</em>?&nbsp;</p>
	<p>In Persian CH we have something like wh- in English, the opening of all those question words like &ldquo;why,&rdquo; &ldquo;who&rdquo; and &ldquo;where.&rdquo; (It&rsquo;s the counterpart of <em>qu</em>- in Latin &mdash; <em>Quis</em>? <em>Quid</em>, <em>Quantus</em>? or in French, pronounced differently &mdash; <em>Qui</em>? <em>Quand</em>? <em>Quoi</em>? <em>Quel heure est-il?</em>) Cheh plays that role in Persian. Alone it means &ldquo;what.&rdquo; <em>Che-ṭowr</em> (&ldquo;by what means, in what manner&rdquo;) is &ldquo;how.&rdquo; &ldquo;<em>&#7716;&acirc;l-e shom&acirc; che-ṭowr ast</em>,&rdquo; &ldquo;How are you?&rdquo; is one of the standard greetings. <em>Chand</em> is &ldquo;how many.&rdquo; <em>Che qadr</em> is &ldquo;how much.&rdquo; <em>Cher&acirc;</em> is &ldquo;why,&rdquo; which (according to some logic I can almost sense but not quite) also means &ldquo;yes.&rdquo; (Why not?) <em>Chun</em> is &ldquo;since,&rdquo; &ldquo;as,&rdquo; &ldquo;because,&rdquo; and a <em>chun-o cher&acirc;</em>, a &ldquo;because and why,&rdquo; is an argument. <em>Cheh </em>plus -<em>ast</em> (&ldquo;is&rdquo;) makes <em>chist</em>. Add <em>&acirc;n</em>, &ldquo;that,&rdquo; or <em>chist &acirc;n</em> &ndash; &ldquo;what is it that &hellip; ?&rdquo; A <em>chist&acirc;n</em>, a &ldquo;what is that,&rdquo; is a noun meaning a riddle. (For instance, this kind of question: what is it that everywhere, but no one sees it? Air. <em>Hav&acirc;</em>. What is it that has two feet and borrows two more, but wherever it goes you can&rsquo;t keep up with it? A bicycle, a <em>dow-charkheh</em>.&nbsp;</p>
	
	<h3>Lamp</h3>
	<p><em>Charkh</em>, a wheel, commonplace enough, has a secondary meaning which takes us beyond the world of household objects. The sky, because it turns, is often simply &ldquo;the wheel.&rdquo; It is often expanded to <em>charkh-e falak</em>, the wheel of the sky. In one of &lsquo;Umar Khayy&acirc;m&rsquo;s quatrains (FitzGerald paraphrased it), the night sky is reduced to just one more household object, the children&rsquo;s toy we know as a magic lantern:</p>
	
	<blockquote>
	<em>In charkh-e falak ke m&acirc; dar u &#7716;ayr&acirc;n-im</em><br>
	<em>F&acirc;nus-e khiy&acirc;l az u math&acirc;li d&acirc;nim</em>:<br>
	<em>Khurshid cher&acirc;gh d&acirc;n-o &lsquo;&acirc;lem f&acirc;nus</em>&mdash;<br>
	<em>M&acirc; chun ṣovar-im k&rsquo;andar-e u gard&acirc;nim</em>.&nbsp;</p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p>[This celestial wheel (<em>charkh-e falak</em>) inside which we stand, amazed-- / let&rsquo;s look at it as a magic lantern: / The sun is the candle (literally a lamp -- <em>cher&acirc;gh</em>); the world, the lamp shade (<em>f&acirc;nus</em>) which encloses it, / and we, like shadowy forms, circle around inside. (Actually I thought of <em>cher&acirc;gh</em> and <em>f&acirc;nus</em> as synonyms, but I stand corrected.)</p>
	</blockquote>

	<blockquote>
	This great carousel on which we ride<br>
	Has the rotating lantern for its model.<br>
	The sun is the lamp, the world its outer shade,<br>
	And we are the images on it, aimlessly floating by.<br>
	&mdash;trans. Karim Emami]
	</blockquote>
	
	
	<p>Astronomy was among Khayyam&rsquo;s skills, though you wouldn&rsquo;t guess it from this quatrain. We don&rsquo;t learn any science from it. Perhaps the opposite. We do learn something though, and it&rsquo;s a little surprising, at least to me, that there was such a thing as a magic lantern already in the 12th century, and it was familiar enough to use as a simile. According to this comparison, the sky is just another children&rsquo;s game. The celestial <em>charkh</em> is just the lamp shade (in FitzGerald&rsquo;s paraphrase, &ldquo;a sun-illumined lantern&rdquo;) with the constellation shapes pin-holed on it. What&rsquo;s inside, playing the role of sun, is a <em>cher&acirc;gh</em>.&nbsp;</p>
	<p><em>Cher&acirc;gh</em>, lamp, can be a word with a mystique, perhaps because its Arabic equivalent (<em>miṣb&acirc;h</em>) figures as a mysterious, mystical object in the Sura called &ldquo;Light&rdquo; (Surat al-N&ucirc;r 24.35). Often too it is just a lamp. In 1979 I was carrying on a correspondence with an Iranian friend in Tehran, who was watching the events of their revolution spiral around him and thinking about history. He had a long memory, and he was in his seventies: he had seen the last Qajar monarch, Ahmad Shah, after that the twenty-year reign of Reza Shah, and he had seen the years of Reza Shah&rsquo;s son Mohammad. He had seen donkey carts crowding the streets; he had seen the gradual accumulation of cars which, generation after generation, persisted in clogging the streets of Tehran, and now he watched airplanes overhead. He wrote with a kind of melancholy about the way history kept disappointing the Iranian observer, and summed it up with a verse proverb, a <em>bayt</em> which has haunted me ever since, with another Cheh question word and another <em>cher&acirc;gh</em>:</p>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p><em>Fereshteh-&icirc; keh vak&icirc;l ast az khaz&acirc;&rsquo;en-e b&acirc;d</em><br>
	<em>Che gham khorad ke navazad cher&acirc;gh-e biveh-zani?</em></p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p>[The angel in charge of the storehouses where the winds are kept: / What sorrow (<em>che</em> <em>gham</em>) does he feel if the widow&rsquo;s <em>cher&acirc;gh</em> blows out?]&nbsp;</p>
	</blockquote>
		
	<p>First you look down at the earth from above: a mortal reader gets a chance for a brief moment to see the world from the point of view of an angel with an important job. We identify with the big forces. Then we see the same forces from underneath, moving from the big powers to take in the scene from the point of view of their victims. The reader may even feel a little guilty at having identified with that angel. Sometimes, perhaps always, history is like a hurricane, blowing out the lamps of powerless people. It&rsquo;s knowledge you can find without looking very far.</p>
	
