	<h3>China</h3>
	<p>&ldquo;<em>Utl&ucirc;b al-&lsquo;ilm, wa law bi al-Ṣ&icirc;n</em>,&rdquo; &ldquo;seek knowledge (<em>al-&lsquo;ilm</em>), even in China&rdquo;: the Arabic proverb is a <em>&#7716;ad&icirc;th</em>, a saying attributed to the Prophet. Ṣ&icirc;n means Persian Ch&icirc;n, the word for China. Ch&icirc;n stems from the name of the Chin Dynasty (255-204 BCE). (Arabic Ṣin is another variation.) The intermediary is Sanskrit. The <em>&#7716;ad&icirc;th</em> recommending China as a place to seek knowledge generates the narrative of &lsquo;Att&acirc;r&rsquo;s 13th-century allegory <em>Manṭiq al-Ṭayr</em>, the conference of the birds. A flock of birds goes on a mission seeking the ultimate bird, the Simorgh, whose spiritual power extends right out to the feathers:</p>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p><em>Dar mi&acirc;n-e Chin fet&acirc;d az vei pari</em><br>
	[In the middle of China one of his feathers fell &hellip;]</p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p><em>Har kasi naqshi az &acirc;n par bar gereft;</em><br>
	<em>Har keh did &acirc;n naqsh k&acirc;ri dar gereft.</em></p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p>[Everyone had an image of it. / Everyone who saw those pictures imagined it in his own way. &ndash;<em>Manṭaq al-ṭayr</em>, 47]</p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<p>The mystical bird which lets a feather drop is like the Lord giving a revelation to mankind. To mankind has been granted the Qur&rsquo;&acirc;n; the people of China are granted a feather, but a feather of mystical power. It&rsquo;s a simple formula: bird, feather, and the people who find it: divinity, holy book, believers. The foreshortening of human history makes the listener feel outside human time. And once that bird called the Simorgh has shed that feather, people in China and in the rest of the world can talk of nothing else:</p>
	
	
	<blockquote>
		<p>&#1570;&#1606; &#1662;&#1585;&#1575;&#1705;&#1606;&#1608;&#1606; &#1583;&#1585; &#1606;&#1711;&#1575;&#1585;&#1587;&#1578;&#1575;&#1606; &#1670;&#1740;&#1606; &#1575;&#1587;&#1578;<br>
		.&#1575;&laquo;&#1575;&#1591;&#1604;&#1608;&#1576; &#1575;&#1604;&#1593;&#1604;&#1604;&#1605; &#1608; &#1604;&#1608; &#1576;&#1575;&#1604;&#1604;&#1589;&#1740;&#1606;&raquo; &#1570;&#1586; &#1575;&#1740;&#1606; &#1575;&#1587;&#1578;		
	</blockquote>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p><em>&Acirc;n par akn&ucirc;n dar nag&acirc;rest&acirc;n-e Chin ast</em>:<br>
	&ldquo;Utl&ucirc;b al-&lsquo;ilm wa law bi al-S&icirc;n&rdquo; <em>az in-ast</em>.</p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p>[That feather now is in the picture gallery of China; / And that&rsquo;s the reason for the phrase <em>Utl&ucirc;b al-`ilm wa law bi al-Ṣin</em>.]</p>
	</blockquote>
		
	<p><em>Chin</em> in Persian isn&rsquo;t the only Chinese word that went abroad. There is a word <em>ch&aacute;</em> in Chinese (&#33590;, second tone), which has entered Persian, retaining the hard CH consonant, as <em>ch&acirc;i</em>. <em>Ch&acirc;&rsquo;&icirc;</em> is a word still heard in British slang, attested as early as the 16th century. (I checked.) In an alternative form, <em>sh&acirc;&rsquo;&icirc;</em>, it enters Arabic dictionaries too, recognizably the same word transposed into a language without the harder sound of Che. <em>Ch&aacute;</em> is also the source of our word &ldquo;tea.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
	<p>When E.G. Browne approached Tehran in November, 1887, his party stopped at a road-side tea-house, adding that it would be his last for a while:&nbsp;</p>
	<p>Many such tea-houses formerly existed in the capital but most of them were closed some time ago by order of the Sh&aacute;h. The reason commonly alleged for this proceeding is that they were supposed to encourage extravagance and idleness, or, as I have also heard, said, evils of a more serious kind. (89)&nbsp;</p>
	<p>Tea houses were reinstated in the 20th century, as travelers can attest. It seems hard to imagine Iran without them.</p>
	
