	<h3>$</h3>
	<p>A transplant from China which took longer to establish itself abroad was Cheh word <em>chav</em> or <em>chao</em>, from Chinese <em>ch&#257;o</em> (1st tone). (The character for <em>chao</em>, &#38046;, consists of the radical for &ldquo;gold&rdquo; on the left and the character for &ldquo;little&rdquo; on the right.) The word <em>ch&#257;o </em>took an interesting turn in the 13th century.</p>
	<p>Hulagu (or H&uuml;leg&uuml;), great grandson of Genghis Khan (in Persian Cheh name Changiz), after destroying Baghdad (656/1258), defined the western boundary of his empire (or rather had the western boundary defined for him), thanks to a famous defeat at the hands of Egyptian Mamluks at &lsquo;Ayn Jalut in Palestine. He went east and set up the Ilkhanate dynasty, with a capital in Tabriz, extending from the areas we now call Iraq to modern Pakistan. His grandson Gaykh&acirc;tu ruled for only four years (1291-1295), and during that short reign is said to have spent cash with wild abandon. In 1294, with the help of his prime minister Sadr-e Jah&acirc;n, his administration experimented with the Chinese system of creating money on paper with block printing. Apparently, with the help of the ambassador from China, where Kubla Khan reigned, Sadr-e Jah&acirc;n designed <em>ch&#257;o</em> (钞) on the Chinese model, including inscriptions in Chinese. In E.G. Browne&rsquo;s description,</p>

	<blockquote>The notes consisted of oblong rectangular pieces of paper inscribed with some words in Chinese, over which stood&hellip; &ldquo;There is no god but God, Muhammad is the Apostle of God,&rdquo; in Arabic. Lower down was the scribe&rsquo;s or designer&rsquo;s name, and the value of the note (which varied from half a <em>dirham</em> to ten <em>d&iacute;n&aacute;r</em>s) inscribed in a circle. A further inscription ran as follows: &ldquo;The King of the world issued this auspicious <em>chao</em> in the year A.H. 693&hellip; Anyone altering or defacing the same shall be put to death, together with his wife and children, and his property shall be forfeited to the exchequer.&rdquo; (Browne, <em>Literary History</em> 3.37-38)</blockquote>

	<p>Browne adds that, with the currency, proclamations were sent to all the major cities under Gaykh&acirc;tu&rsquo;s administration, answering imagined objections to the new currency, and appending a couplet in Persian:</p>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p><strong><em>Ch&acirc;v</em></strong><em> agar dar jah&acirc;n rav&acirc;n gardad -- Rownaq-e malek j&acirc;vd&acirc;n garded.</em></p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p>[If in the world this<em> chao </em>(<em>ch&acirc;v</em>) gains currency,/ Immortal shall the Empire&rsquo;s glory be. --Browne&rsquo;s translation, <em>Literary History</em>, 3.38]</p>
	</blockquote>
	
	<p>The word c<em>h&acirc;v</em> (or <em>ch&acirc;w</em>), i.e. <em>ch&acirc;p</em>, can still be found in Turkish or Persian dictionaries, if they&rsquo;re big enough. Gaykh&acirc;tu issued them, but the public&rsquo;s refusal to use them was universal. They never became current (<em>rav&acirc;n</em>), and he was obliged to withdraw them. Gayk&acirc;skhtu did not become <em>j&acirc;vd&acirc;n</em>, &ldquo;immortal,&rdquo; except in the sense you can still find his name in the books of specialists and dilettantes. The conditional in the couplet (<em>agar</em>&mdash; the <em>chao </em>catches on) seems in retrospect the key word.&nbsp;</p>
	<p>Since then a tradition of paper currency has become perfectly respectable both in Europe and in the world where the Arabic script dominates, but it took a while. (In the Ottoman empire it began in 1840, under Abdulmecit. In Iran, paper currency begins in 1890, under Shah Nasir al-Din.) Today the term for it in Persian is a loan word, <em>esken&acirc;s</em>, which traces back to the French term <em>assignat</em>, the paper money issued in revolutionary France in the 1790s.&nbsp;</p>
	<p>You will find a few words in Arabic script on the back side of Chinese paper currency, among five scripts which represent the five major peoples. (Actually they could have included a lot more than five.) The first, written at the upper right in Roman letters (what in Chinese is called <em>pīn yīn</em>), says, in Chinese, <em>Zh&#333;ng-gu&oacute;</em> <em>r&eacute;nm&iacute;n y&iacute;nh&aacute;ng</em>, &ldquo;The People&rsquo;s Bank of China.&rdquo; <em>Zh&#333;ng-gu&oacute;</em> is China; <em>r&eacute;nm&iacute;n </em>is &ldquo;people,&rdquo; as in <em>r&eacute;nm&iacute;nb&igrave;</em>, RMB, the Chinese currency; <em>y&iacute;nh&aacute;ng</em> is &ldquo;bank.&rdquo;) Anyone who knows the Roman script could sound out the letters. The other four, in two rows underneath, are more of a challenge. They represent four more peoples, the same four represented by the small stars on the Chinese flag. The top row is, on the left, Mongolian, on the right, Tibetan. The second on the lower row is Zhu&agrave;ng, the largest minority, from Guangxi in the south (written in <em>pīn yīn</em>).&nbsp;</p>
	<p>The lower left language is the language of Uighurs in the west of China. Its appearance on the money is one piece of evidence among others that the central Chinese like to keep the Uighurs close. The language, a variant of Turkish, is written in Arabic script:</p>
	
	<blockquote>
	<p>&#1580;&#1735;&#1709;&#1711;&#1608; &#1582;&#1749; &#1604;&#1602; &#1576;&#1575;&#1606;&#1603;&#1587;&#1609;&#1609;</p>
	</blockquote>
		
	<blockquote>
	<p><em>...jung-gow khalq bankesi</em>.&nbsp;</p>
	</blockquote>
		
	<p>The Uighur words in Arabic script are first the denomination, then three loan words: 1) <em>Jung-gow </em>transcribes the Chinese word <em>Zh&#333;ng-gu&oacute;</em>, the middle country, i.e. China. 2) <em>Khalq</em>, from the Arabic <em>khalaqa</em>, &ldquo;to create&rdquo; is an Arabic noun meaning &ldquo;creation,&rdquo; i.e. &ldquo;people.&rdquo; (In Chinese it would have been <em>r&eacute;n-m&iacute;n</em>.) In this case it&rsquo;s the bank of the <em>khalq</em>, the people&rsquo;s bank. 3) As for &ldquo;bank,&rdquo; it&rsquo;s just the English word &ldquo;bank,&rdquo; one of those loan words which shows up regularly in European and Middle Eastern language. 4) The Uighur suffix -<em>esi</em> in <em>bankesi</em>, is the first indigenous element, a kind of possessive (&ldquo;its bank&rdquo;) which plays a role common in numerous Turkish dialects. <em>Zh&#333;ng-gu&oacute; khalq bankesi.</em> Six syllables, four major language groups. Chinese, Arabic, English, and a Turkic suffix.</p>

	<h3>Two Kinds of Printing</h3>
	<p>The contemporary Persian word <em>ch&acirc;p</em>, &ldquo;printing&rdquo; (pronounced like English &ldquo;chop&rdquo;) sounds as if it too might be a loan word from Chinese. After all, when you visit China you find that the molds used in block-printing are referred to in English as &ldquo;chops.&rdquo; &ldquo;Chop&rdquo; turns out to be a loan-word in Chinese as well, evidently from Hindi, where <em>chhap</em> means &ldquo;imprint, stamp, publication.&rdquo; Whatever the origin of the word, some kind of printing comes twice to Iran &mdash; once from China in Gaykh&acirc;tu&rsquo;s day and then definitively, in the 19th century, from the other direction, the kind with movable type.&nbsp;</p>
	
		<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/cheh5.png" width="380" align="right" style="margin-right:-80px" /></p>
	
	<p><em>Chidan</em> is the verb in Persian for picking (e.g. flowers), collecting, arranging, setting a table. One form of the verb (its root) is <em>chin</em> (homonym of Chin, &ldquo;China&rdquo;). <em>&#7716;oruf-chini</em> is typesetting. (<em>&#7716;oruf</em> are letters. You pluck letters out of the case.) In English the word &ldquo;setting&rdquo; emphasizes the act of putting the letters into the composing stick. In Persian the emphasis is a step earlier in the process, on the act of choosing the letters out of their case. The difference is probably arbitrary, but it makes sense. The pieces of print to choose from make <em>&#7716;oruf-chini</em> a bit more elaborate. You need more pieces of type than you do with the Roman alphabet. It can be a lot more: &ldquo;A complete font, including vowel marks for recording the Koran and other vocalized texts, runs to more than six hundred, plus huge quantities of leads and quadrats [the pieces of a font which are blank] to be placed between vowel marks and lines&rdquo; (Sheila Blair, <em>Arabic Calligraphy</em>, 487). It&rsquo;s just as well she doesn&rsquo;t itemize, and it&rsquo;s clear that most presses didn&rsquo;t have a full set of 600. She adds, &ldquo;The 24-point Arabic font developed for the French Imprimerie Nationale in the nineteenth century filled four cases and contained 710 different sorts&rdquo; (ibid). And yet it was possible somehow to accommodate all the letters and their variations. (It was certainly easier than Chinese, whose early presses are said to have had an arsenal of 60,000 characters.)&nbsp;</p>
	<p>The typewriter eliminates the need for a <em>&#7716;oruf-chin</em>. Its letters are already there in front of you. The typewriter which generates Arabic script encounters some extra difficulties, not just because the cylinder moves the other way, but because the number of necessary character shapes is considerably greater &ndash; not 710, but enough to require some ingenuity. There&rsquo;s a story about how the ingenuity came to be. It has to do with two inventors &mdash; Selim Hadadd (Syrian) and Philippe Waked (Lebanese-Egyptian) &mdash; working separately, both of whom applied for a patent in 1899. (There&rsquo;s a full account on a <a href="https://kerningcultures.com/kerned-and-cultured/arabic-typewriter">Kerning Cultures</a> podcast.) The problem an Arabic keyboard has to overcome has to do not with the number of letters (28 or 32), but with another complication. On the familiar western keyboard you have only two forms for each Roman letter &mdash; uppercase and lowercase. All you have to do is press the shift key and get from one to the other. Capitals aren&rsquo;t an issue for Arabic, but for most Arabic letters you do have those three forms: initial, medial or terminal. What you need is a system where two settings can show all three. The first step is to invent a keyboard where you press the &ldquo;shift&rdquo; key and get the terminal or stand-alone form. The complicated part is to design a font in which both the initial and medial forms are both recognizable and identical. That is, each letter will have to be able to start a word or to connect on both sides. For one thing, you need to design them on a single base line, so when the letters need to connect they will line up against one another, usually with a tiny space between.&nbsp;</p>
	<p>The three Arabic letters with the Jim shape, for instance, have the pointed side right at the edge, at the same height where the preceding letter will touch there (or almost). The lower arc of the letter needs to curve down slightly and then rise just to that level, to connect to the next letter. At that same height. The three are lined up together at the upper right of the keyboard, where O, P and &ldquo;[&ldquo; are located on the Roman QWERTY equivalent. On a Persian keyboard you would find Cheh on the upper right, next to the other three, tucked into the corner like an afterthought.&nbsp;</p>

